1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,200
On the 24th of February, 2022,

2
00:00:04,300 --> 00:00:08,600
at five in the morning
Moscow time,

3
00:00:08,700 --> 00:00:13,200
Russia launched its full-scale
invasion of Ukraine.

4
00:00:13,300 --> 00:00:17,500
In the seventy-two hours
that followed,

5
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:22,000
the MOEX index collapsed
forty-five percent.

6
00:00:22,100 --> 00:00:26,500
The ruble lost thirty percent
of its value in days.

7
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:31,000
And European natural gas prices
—the TTF benchmark—

8
00:00:31,100 --> 00:00:36,000
began a climb that would take them
more than ten times higher.

9
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:41,500
How many fund managers and investors
with exposure to those assets

10
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:46,000
had incorporated that risk
into their models?

11
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Fewer than forty percent of the market
assigned a meaningful probability.

12
00:00:52,100 --> 00:00:57,000
Even with troop concentration signals
available in public sources

13
00:00:57,100 --> 00:01:01,000
since November
the year before.

14
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,000
That gap between the signal and the price
is the problem this course solves.

15
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:11,500
Welcome to Zenith Academia.

16
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:15,500
I'm an analyst
at Zenith Rise Capital.

17
00:01:15,600 --> 00:01:20,000
Over the next twenty-eight minutes
we're going to build a practical framework

18
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:25,000
for identifying, measuring and integrating
geopolitical risk into investment decisions.

19
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,500
We are not doing geopolitics
for its own intellectual pleasure.

20
00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:34,500
We're doing it because
it has a price.

21
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:39,500
There is a spread widening,
a currency depreciation,

22
00:01:39,600 --> 00:01:44,000
a margin collapse behind every
material geopolitical event.

23
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:49,500
Three data points to move this
from intuition to evidence.

24
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:55,000
First: every major disruption
in the Strait of Hormuz since 1973

25
00:01:55,100 --> 00:02:00,000
has generated an average crude oil spike
of twenty to forty percent.

26
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Second: sovereign bond spreads widen
300–1,500 basis points

27
00:02:06,100 --> 00:02:11,000
in the year before the event.
The year before.

28
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:15,500
The signal was in the market
before anyone called it news.

29
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Third: emerging-market currencies absorb
fifteen to thirty-five percent depreciation

30
00:02:21,100 --> 00:02:25,500
in the twelve months following
a material geopolitical escalation.

31
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:30,500
Geopolitical risk already has a price.

32
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:35,000
What most investors are missing
is the framework to read it.

33
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,000
And that is exactly what we're going
to build together today.

34
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:50,000
[Pause · Section transition]

35
00:02:50,500 --> 00:03:00,000
The ZRC Framework · Four Layers
of Geopolitical Risk.

36
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:05,000
The most common mistake I see
in geopolitical analysis applied

37
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:09,500
to investment is not a lack of information.
Today there is plenty of that.

38
00:03:09,600 --> 00:03:14,500
The mistake is collapsing everything
into one blurry category —

39
00:03:14,600 --> 00:03:19,500
"country risk", "political risk" —
blending phenomena with different horizons.

40
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:25,000
A country can have fragile institutions
going back decades — structural risk —

41
00:03:25,100 --> 00:03:30,000
and at the same time be experiencing
a balance-of-payments crisis right now.

42
00:03:30,100 --> 00:03:35,000
And simultaneously have a border conflict
cutting a specific supply chain.

43
00:03:35,100 --> 00:03:40,000
Four distinct phenomena.
If we analyse them as one,

44
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:45,000
we will never know which is dominant,
which is transitory,

45
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:49,500
which actually warrants action.
At ZRC, we call this:

46
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:54,000
the Four-Layer Framework.

47
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The first layer is the structural layer.
This is the long-run substrate.

48
00:04:00,100 --> 00:04:05,000
The quality of state institutions,
social cohesion,

49
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:10,000
the country's geopolitical positioning
in the international system.

50
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:15,500
Changes at this layer are slow.
They are measured in decades.

51
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:20,500
But they determine the ceiling of
risk-adjusted returns sustainably available.

52
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
A country with weak institutions
can deliver extraordinary short-term returns.

53
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:31,000
Carry trades in fragile currencies
can be spectacular while they last.

54
00:04:31,100 --> 00:04:36,000
But the permanent valuation ceiling
is constrained by the structural risk premium.

55
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
Key variables: Rule of Law Index,
Fragile States Index,

56
00:04:42,100 --> 00:04:47,000
positioning in military
and commercial alliances.

57
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:53,000
The second layer is the regulatory layer.
It operates over the medium term.

58
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:58,000
It captures all normative changes
driven by political decisions:

59
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:03,000
international sanctions,
capital controls,

60
00:05:03,100 --> 00:05:08,000
foreign investment restrictions,
confiscatory tax changes.

61
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:14,000
This layer has gained critical relevance
since 2022. Here is why:

62
00:05:14,100 --> 00:05:19,000
Western democracies demonstrated they would
weaponise the international financial system

63
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:24,000
— SWIFT access, central bank reserves,
dollar settlement —

64
00:05:24,100 --> 00:05:28,500
as a geopolitical pressure tool.

65
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:34,000
The immobilisation of three hundred billion
in Russian central bank reserves

66
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:39,000
was an act without modern precedent
in the financial system.

67
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:45,000
The third layer is the operational layer.
Most immediate for earnings impact.

68
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:50,000
Supply chain disruption,
severed access to critical infrastructure,

69
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:55,000
interruption of transport routes,
loss of access to critical inputs.

70
00:05:55,500 --> 00:06:00,500
These events tend to be sudden
and high-visibility.

71
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:05,500
But they also carry — in many cases —
greater reversibility once resolved.

72
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:11,000
The fourth layer is the market layer.
It captures how the first three

73
00:06:11,100 --> 00:06:16,000
translate into observable signals:
widening spreads,

74
00:06:16,100 --> 00:06:21,000
currency depreciation,
portfolio capital outflows,

75
00:06:21,100 --> 00:06:26,000
elevated sector volatility,
safe-haven asset appreciation.

76
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,000
This layer is the noisiest
in the short term.

77
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:37,000
Markets overreact.
Then correct.

78
00:06:37,100 --> 00:06:42,000
But it is also where the best
entry and exit opportunities lie

79
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:47,000
for investors with a solid analytical
framework in the upstream layers.

80
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:53,000
One key idea before we move on:
the four layers are not independent.

81
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:58,000
An operational shock without underlying
structural weakness

82
00:06:58,100 --> 00:07:02,500
tends to be transitory.

83
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:08,000
Severity and reversibility are read
by assessing how many layers

84
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:13,000
are simultaneously
compromised.

85
00:07:13,100 --> 00:07:18,000
The more layers in play at once,
the more persistent the impact.

86
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:24,000
That is the framework.
Now let us see how it reaches price.

87
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:30,000
[Pause · Section transition]

88
00:07:30,500 --> 00:07:37,000
Transmission Channels
to Asset Prices.

89
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:43,000
Identifying the geopolitical risk
is the first step.

90
00:07:43,100 --> 00:07:48,000
The second — more demanding
and more rewarding —

91
00:07:48,100 --> 00:07:53,000
is tracing the mechanism by which
that risk reaches asset prices.

92
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000
There is an enormous difference between
knowing there is tension in the Red Sea

93
00:07:59,100 --> 00:08:04,500
and knowing exactly which margins
will compress, by how much and when.

94
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,500
The first is an observation.
The second is an investment input.

95
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,500
There are four primary
transmission channels.

96
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:21,000
The first: the energy channel.
The most direct and most studied.

97
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:26,000
Producer and consumer states have
historically used energy flows

98
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:31,000
as a political pressure tool.

99
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:36,500
The first-round mechanism:
any disruption in energy production

100
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:41,500
or transport raises the cost
of those inputs for everyone.

101
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:47,000
The second-round mechanism
is what most analysts underestimate.

102
00:08:47,100 --> 00:08:52,000
Higher energy costs
compress industrial margins,

103
00:08:52,100 --> 00:08:57,000
push inflation upward,
force rates higher for longer,

104
00:08:57,100 --> 00:09:02,000
and reduce consumer purchasing power,
deteriorating aggregate growth.

105
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:08,000
The clearest recent example:
Russia's gas curtailment to Europe in 2022.

106
00:09:08,100 --> 00:09:13,000
The TTF climbed
more than ten times from its lows.

107
00:09:13,500 --> 00:09:18,500
It precipitated an industrial crisis
in chemicals, fertilisers, aluminium, glass.

108
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:24,000
Germany revised its growth projections
down 1.5–2.5 GDP percentage points.

109
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:28,500
That is not noise.
That is a price factor with a name.

110
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:35,000
The second channel:
supply chains.

111
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:40,000
Three decades of globalisation
have created ultra-efficient

112
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:44,500
but deeply fragile supply chains.

113
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Many sectors depend on components
manufactured in few geographies.

114
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:55,500
Vulnerabilities that only become visible
when geopolitical tension activates them.

115
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:01,000
Think for a moment
about semiconductors.

116
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:06,000
TSMC manufactures in Taiwan
between sixty and ninety-two percent

117
00:10:06,100 --> 00:10:11,000
of the world's advanced chip production,
depending on the technology node.

118
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:16,500
Not sixty percent of one type.
Sixty to ninety-two percent of all of them.

119
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:22,000
What would happen if there were
a disruption in Taiwan?

120
00:10:22,100 --> 00:10:27,000
Not necessarily an invasion.
A partial naval blockade would be enough.

121
00:10:27,100 --> 00:10:32,000
The impact would propagate immediately
to automotive, consumer electronics,

122
00:10:32,100 --> 00:10:37,000
medical equipment and defence
production worldwide.

123
00:10:37,500 --> 00:10:42,500
Does your analysis of companies
with advanced semiconductor exposure

124
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:47,000
include that vulnerability
or ignore it?

125
00:10:48,500 --> 00:10:53,500
The third channel:
currencies and capital flows.

126
00:10:53,600 --> 00:10:58,500
In periods of elevated uncertainty,
capital migrates to safe havens:

127
00:10:58,600 --> 00:11:03,500
dollars, Swiss francs,
Treasuries and gold.

128
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
But the most important story
in this channel over recent years

129
00:11:09,100 --> 00:11:14,000
is not private capital movement.
It is the weaponisation of finance.

130
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:19,500
When the West immobilised three hundred
billion in Russian central bank reserves,

131
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:24,500
it was not just a sanction.
It was a message to every central bank.

132
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:30,000
If your geopolitical positioning
conflicts with Western interests,

133
00:11:30,100 --> 00:11:35,000
your reserves in dollars and euros
are not safe.

134
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:41,000
The consequences of that precedent
are still unfolding.

135
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:46,000
The acceleration in reserve diversification
toward gold and renminbi

136
00:11:46,100 --> 00:11:50,500
in emerging-market central banks
is not coincidence.

137
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:55,000
It is a rational response
to a risk once considered theoretical.

138
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
The fourth channel:
risk premia.

139
00:12:02,100 --> 00:12:07,000
The most abstract, perhaps the most pervasive.
Geopolitics affects the discount rate

140
00:12:07,100 --> 00:12:12,000
investors apply to future cash flows
from geopolitically exposed assets.

141
00:12:12,500 --> 00:12:17,500
This premium rarely appears labelled.
It surfaces as a valuation discount

142
00:12:17,600 --> 00:12:22,000
or a multiple haircut.
But it is real and measurable.

143
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:27,500
In 2023, European energy infrastructure
with Eastern Europe exposure

144
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:32,500
traded at discounts of fifteen
to twenty-five percent vs peers.

145
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:38,000
Not explained by operational fundamentals.
Explained by the geopolitical risk premium.

146
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:43,500
Two types of situations result:
assets that deserve the discount

147
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:48,000
and assets that are undervalued because
the market premium is excessive.

148
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:53,000
The analytical framework is what allows you
to tell them apart.

149
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:00,000
[Pause · Section transition]

150
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:07,000
The ZRC Geopolitical Scoring
Methodology. From signal to decision.

151
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:13,000
We have covered what geopolitical risk is,
how it breaks down into layers

152
00:13:13,100 --> 00:13:18,000
and how it reaches asset prices.
Now comes the question I get most often.

153
00:13:18,500 --> 00:13:23,500
"This all sounds compelling,
but how do I turn it into a number?"

154
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:29,000
"How does this
enter my model?"

155
00:13:29,500 --> 00:13:33,500
It is exactly the right question.
And it has an answer.

156
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:39,000
The primary obstacle is not
a lack of information.

157
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:44,000
It is the difficulty of converting
largely qualitative information

158
00:13:44,100 --> 00:13:49,000
into a quantitative input
that can enter decision models.

159
00:13:49,500 --> 00:13:54,000
The ZRC Scoring Methodology
solves that in four steps.

160
00:13:55,500 --> 00:14:00,500
Step one:
the exposure inventory.

161
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:05,500
Before evaluating anything, map all
the geopolitical exposures of the asset:

162
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:10,500
geographies where it operates,
countries its supply chain depends on,

163
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:15,500
markets where it sells,
currencies in which it reports.

164
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:21,000
This inventory is not
a one-time exercise.

165
00:14:21,100 --> 00:14:26,000
Update it whenever the asset changes
its operating model

166
00:14:26,100 --> 00:14:31,000
or whenever the geopolitical environment
of any relevant geography changes.

167
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:37,000
Step two:
the layer-by-layer evaluation.

168
00:14:37,100 --> 00:14:42,000
For each geography identified,
assess the four ZRC layers

169
00:14:42,100 --> 00:14:47,000
on a scale of one to five.
One is minimal risk, five is severe.

170
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:52,500
This assessment draws on primary
and secondary sources:

171
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:57,500
IMF, World Bank, OECD,
Oxford Analytica, Eurasia Group.

172
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:03,000
Step three:
weighting by transmission channel.

173
00:15:03,100 --> 00:15:08,000
Not all layers carry equal weight
for every asset.

174
00:15:08,100 --> 00:15:13,000
A manufacturer should weight
the operational layer more heavily.

175
00:15:13,100 --> 00:15:18,000
A financial entity with sovereign debt
should weight regulatory more heavily.

176
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:23,500
Weights are documented explicitly —
not as bureaucracy,

177
00:15:23,600 --> 00:15:28,500
but so they can be revisited
when circumstances change.

178
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:34,000
Step four: the composite score
and decision thresholds.

179
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:39,000
Multiply scores by weights, sum the layers:
a number between one and five.

180
00:15:39,500 --> 00:15:44,500
Score 1.0–2.0: low risk.
Routine quarterly monitoring.

181
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:49,500
2.1–3.5: moderate risk.
Enhanced monitoring plus scenario analysis.

182
00:15:49,600 --> 00:15:54,500
Above 3.6: elevated risk.
Deep due diligence and active hedging.

183
00:15:55,500 --> 00:16:00,500
Before the case study, let me be direct
about what this scoring cannot do.

184
00:16:00,600 --> 00:16:05,500
It does not capture genuine black-swan
events well.

185
00:16:05,600 --> 00:16:10,500
It does not eliminate analyst bias.
And it can create false precision

186
00:16:10,600 --> 00:16:15,500
if we forget the scores are expert
judgements, not objective facts.

187
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:21,000
Its value is in structuring the analysis
and forcing explicit assumptions —

188
00:16:21,100 --> 00:16:26,000
not producing a number
that replaces human judgement.

189
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:32,000
[Pause · Section transition]

190
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:39,000
Case Study. Let us apply
everything we have covered.

191
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:44,500
The asset: a mid-size European industrial
company, revenue ~€800 million.

192
00:16:44,600 --> 00:16:49,500
Precision machinery manufacturer
with supply chain in East Asia.

193
00:16:49,600 --> 00:16:54,500
Sixty-five percent of critical components
transit through the Red Sea and Suez Canal.

194
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:00,000
The trigger: escalation of Houthi attacks
in the Red Sea, November 2023.

195
00:17:00,100 --> 00:17:05,000
And the decision of major shipping lines
to reroute via the Cape of Good Hope.

196
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:11,000
We apply the ZRC Framework.
Structural layer: Yemen.

197
00:17:11,100 --> 00:17:16,000
Yemen has been in active civil war since
2014. Structural fragility, no resolution.

198
00:17:16,100 --> 00:17:21,000
Score: four out of five.
Not new information in November 2023.

199
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:26,000
It had been observable
for nearly a decade.

200
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:32,000
Regulatory layer: Houthi operations
did not generate direct sanctions

201
00:17:32,100 --> 00:17:37,000
for the company, but activated
the European naval operation Aspides.

202
00:17:37,100 --> 00:17:42,000
Modified the marine insurance context
in the zone. Score: two out of five.

203
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:48,000
Operational layer: here the impact
was immediate and material.

204
00:17:48,100 --> 00:17:53,000
Transit times extended
by ten to fourteen days.

205
00:17:53,100 --> 00:17:58,000
Freight rates tripled.
Hull and cargo insurance multiplied 5–10x.

206
00:17:58,500 --> 00:18:03,500
For the company: higher working capital,
pressure on fixed-price contracts,

207
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:08,500
delivery delays that triggered
contractual penalty clauses.

208
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:13,000
Score: five out of five. Severe impact.

209
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:19,000
Market layer: shares of companies
with high Asia-Europe logistics dependence

210
00:18:19,100 --> 00:18:24,000
corrected eight to fifteen percent
in January–February 2024.

211
00:18:24,100 --> 00:18:29,000
The sector traded at a P/E discount
of 1.5–2 turns below historical average.

212
00:18:29,500 --> 00:18:34,000
Score: three out of five.

213
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:40,000
With weights for this asset:
45% operational, 20% structural,

214
00:18:40,100 --> 00:18:45,000
20% market, 15% regulatory,
the composite score comes to:

215
00:18:45,100 --> 00:18:50,000
3.85. Elevated risk.

216
00:18:50,500 --> 00:18:55,500
Which would have triggered deep due diligence
and evaluation of active hedges.

217
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:01,000
I want to pause and make a point
that I think is central.

218
00:19:01,100 --> 00:19:06,000
Yemen's structural fragility — layer one —
had been visible for nearly a decade.

219
00:19:06,100 --> 00:19:11,000
The company's dependence
on the Asia-Suez corridor

220
00:19:11,100 --> 00:19:16,000
was in its annual reports,
in its supplier contracts.

221
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:22,000
Geopolitical analysis of an asset
does not begin when the crisis erupts.

222
00:19:22,100 --> 00:19:27,000
It begins at initial due diligence.

223
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:32,500
Investors who incorporated the Red Sea
corridor's vulnerability

224
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:37,500
into their risk analysis were positioned
to act when the escalation came.

225
00:19:37,600 --> 00:19:42,000
Those who had not
were left reacting.

226
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:48,000
[Pause · Section transition]

227
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:55,000
Synthesis. Three ideas
to take away.

228
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:01,000
First: geopolitical risk already has
a price in markets.

229
00:20:01,100 --> 00:20:06,000
Not incorporating it is implicitly
pricing it at zero.

230
00:20:06,100 --> 00:20:11,000
And in nearly every case,
that is wrong.

231
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:17,000
Second: the ZRC Four-Layer Framework
allows disaggregation of what would

232
00:20:17,100 --> 00:20:22,000
otherwise be a vague, unmanageable category
into variables with distinct horizons,

233
00:20:22,100 --> 00:20:27,000
distinct mechanisms
and distinct reversibility profiles.

234
00:20:27,500 --> 00:20:32,500
That converts qualitative analysis
into actionable quantitative inputs.

235
00:20:33,500 --> 00:20:38,500
Third: the geopolitical score does not
replace analytical judgement —

236
00:20:38,600 --> 00:20:43,500
it structures it.
Its value is in forcing explicitness:

237
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:48,500
compelling you to name the exposures,
the layers at risk and the channels.

238
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:53,000
What you name, you can manage.
What remains implicit, you cannot.

239
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:59,500
If you have found this framework useful —
and I hope you have found it

240
00:20:59,600 --> 00:21:04,500
practical and directly applicable —
here is what comes next in Zenith Academia.

241
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:10,000
The next module, ZRC-ACAD-ENE-02,
goes deep into energy markets

242
00:21:10,100 --> 00:21:15,000
and geopolitics: OPEC+ moves,
LNG redeployment, energy-intensive sectors.

243
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:20,500
The third course, ZRC-ACAD-SCH-03,
works through critical supply chains:

244
00:21:20,600 --> 00:21:25,500
semiconductors, lithium, rare earths,
and reshoring as structural trend.

245
00:21:26,500 --> 00:21:31,500
And if you want to go beyond
the course format, the Inner Circle

246
00:21:31,600 --> 00:21:36,500
gives you access to the weekly
ZRC Intelligence briefing.

247
00:21:36,600 --> 00:21:41,500
Where we apply exactly this framework
to the week's events in real time.

248
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:47,000
And to ZRC Observatory,
our near-real-time

249
00:21:47,100 --> 00:21:52,000
geopolitical signal
monitoring platform.

250
00:21:53,500 --> 00:21:58,500
The world is changing faster than
the models most of us use to analyse it.

251
00:21:58,600 --> 00:22:03,500
The competitive advantage in this
environment is not having more data.

252
00:22:03,600 --> 00:22:08,500
It is having a better framework
for reading it.

253
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:15,000
That is what we do at ZRC.

254
00:22:15,100 --> 00:22:20,000
And it is what we want to teach you
to do at Zenith Academia.

255
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:26,000
See you in the next module.

256
00:22:27,000 --> 00:28:00,000
[Closing music · Zenith Academia]

